column1: At close of business on 1 February 2023, will the upper limit of the Federal Reserve's target range for the federal funds rate be lower, the same, or higher than it was at close of business on 14 December 2022?
column6: ['Business', 'Economic Policy', 'US Policy']
Fed has managed expectations for a rate rise.
It will not be declining yet. No one has suggested that it could
All in
Should be higher considering the current situation.
Market still pricing 100% for a rate hike next FOMC meeting
Polymarket currently gives a mere 7% probability for "same" (they do not even have a market for "lower"): https://polymarket.com/event/fed-interest-rates

Market pricing in 100% chance of continued hike on 2/1/2023. I agree since Fed doesn't need to keep the FF rate the same / cut even if there are data supporting a slowing inflation. The Fed will only do so when we have a longer track record showing inflation slowdown. Leaving 1% chance of "same" for some margin of error - some sort of black swan event that makes the fed decide to keep the same FF rate.
Acquiescing slightly to the crowd...

Given this situation, we remain happy with our call for a further 50bp rate hike at the 1 February Federal Open Market Committee meeting. - ING, Dec 14, https://think.ing.com/articles/a-hawkish-50bp-rate-hike-as-the-fed-pushes-back-against-the-market/
https://image.cnbcfm.com/api/v1/image/107166341-1671045439912-dotpolt.JPG

I expect we'll see another .5-.75 in the Dec meeting and then would see at least .25-.5 in the Jan/Feb meeting. Allowing 10% error on this but it seems the Fed of late has been signaling strongly and sticking to the plan to avoid throwing any surprises.
Strong jobs data: https://www.marketwatch.com/story/job-data-puts-jumbo-0-75-percentage-point-rate-hike-back-on-table-at-feds-december-meeting-11670005000
Oops
All in.

Powell's speech today signaled a rate hike slowdown. 50 bps hike in Dec then 25 bps in Feb seems most likely. Possible but less likely that they hike in Dec then stop in Feb. Possible but very unlikely that the economy tanks between now and Feb enough to cut.
Might be a raise again. US economy is still struggling. Strange, in Europe a slight economy growth feels like a recession. It should be a moderat raise.
The Fed is more likely to hold the rate steady with inflation rapidly declining: https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf
The title of this FT piece arguably captures well the current consensus:

The fed hinted that in 2023 we'll see a lower increases (.5 or .25 vs the .75 of this meeting) but I think it is most likely still an increase and not a pause. I think we'll have the pause in 2023 with almost-complete certainty and I would put a strong guess on seeing lower rates in the back half of the year, especially if the increases in the early part of the year remain aggressive. For now, I'm going 4:1 on higher vs same and putting no chance of a lower rate.
Here is Bloomberg (Oct 30), before today's announcement of the 75bps hike - https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-10-30/goldman-sachs-now-sees-fed-rates-peaking-at-5-in-march

Today (Nov 2) had another 75 basis point increase in the upper target of the Federal Funds Rate. Analysts seem to think that the Fed will keep increasing the target but in 25 basis point increases for the next two meetings.
Fed is slowing down. There are discussions about moderate raises or holding the interest rates. As @bbuckley pointet out https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1532885

The elevated inflation figures, coupled with additional signs pointing to a resilient labour market, also fanned fears that the 0.75 percentage point pace would be extended to December, with another half-point rise expected for February. - FT, Oct 25, https://www.ft.com/content/963bc01e-c81a-462c-ac2b-ef838cb8bc39
From a Wall Street Journal Article:
If the Fed raises 75 bp in November and 50 in December I think it’s more probable they’ll pause in January

The elevated inflation figures, coupled with additional signs pointing to a resilient labour market, also fanned fears that 0.75 percentage-point pace will be extended to December, with another half-point rate rise expected for February. - FT, Oct 20, https://www.ft.com/content/963bc01e-c81a-462c-ac2b-ef838cb8bc39
CME FedWatch market odds

We then look for two 25 bps rate hikes in February and March 2023, with the fed funds rate target range reaching a peak of 4.75%-5.00%. In our view, rate cuts are not on the menu until Q4-2023 - Wells Fargo, Oct 14, https://wellsfargo.bluematrix.com/links2/html/51e1ff2c-a31a-49a5-aa88-cea7e9f5db8d
Feeling more certain about the outcome.

For the first meeting of 2023 in February, Barclays foresees a rate hike of 50 basis points, up from its past forecast of 25 basis points: https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/inflation-federal-reserve-rate-hikes-september-report-economy-meetings-powell-2022-10
Market odds per CME FedWatch
The recent low unemployment result and barely tapering inflation figures "higher" is increasingly likely.
Over the course of the increases, the FED increased by 25 basis points (bp) at first, then 50, then most recently two increases of 75 bp.
The recent low unemployment result and barely tapering inflation figures "higher" is increasingly likely.
Contrary to popular belief:
According to the Atlanta Federal Reserve, based on the Taylor Rule, the Federal Funds Rate should be somewhere between 5% and 7%. https://www.atlantafed.org/cqer/research/taylor-rule?panel=1
Rates are going up all over Europe, there's probably a delay on this trend reaching the US, but by December and February it should be clear.
Inflation won't have come down enough by then, for Fed to reverse or pause rate-hike path

The fed hinted that they would keep raising rates into 2023 even at the cost of a recession. I think there is a solid chance they will pause for a meeting, but see no chance of a decrease so soon after their aggressive increases.
Post-mid term elections rates may be raised again to get the "pain" in place as soon as possible before the 2024 election cycle starts.
Recession fears will be pervasive among economic forecasters, while inflation will continue to be hot.
https://www.cmegroup.com/trading/interest-rates/countdown-to-fomc.html#

Expecting two more raises this year. Would be wise for the Fed to take a pause after that. The market needs some time to adjust.
Just a placeholder; will conduct a probabilistic analysis tomorrow...
Expecting two more big raises this year. Would be unusual for the Fed to take a sudden pause on rate hikes after that. The increase at the end of Jan be smaller (eg 0.25%) but unlikely to be 0%.
Too many factors to make a high probability percentage.
